<center><table border=0><tr><td><center><H2><font face=arial>Re: A question...</font></H2></center>
<font face=arial size=2><b>Posted By:</b> <A HREF="/cgi-local/whois2.cgi?The Beggar">The Beggar</a><br>
<b>Posted On:</b> 11:28 p.m. 8/2/1999<br>
<b>Subject:</b> Re: A question...<p>
<br><center><img src="http://www.everworld.net/pvpquest/images/divider.gif" width=452 height=22 border=0></center><BR><P ALIGN=CENTER><b>In Reply To:</b> <A HREF="http://www.everworld.net/cgi-local/quest.cgi?read=14" TARGET=_self>A question...</A> (Matt)
</STRONG><FONT SIZE=2 color=#FFFFFF FACE=arial>
<P>The beggar knows! The beggar raves! But it it your quest, that the beggar saves?

<P>If ya do follow the story of the Sundering, it did begin by one lowly character who created two lowly characters. Before it garnered the support of the gods, it had the attention of a great many people. It doesn't take GM support to run a quest, you just have to be creative. Why does every quest have to end with an event, or with a magic object? Some quests have socio-political value; some are just fun RP.
<P>Use yer heads, ya louts! Or the beggar will hit you in your snouts!
<P>&gt; Let's say I came up with a large quest for EQ, would the GMs
<BR>&gt; support it in any way? If the answer is yes, then how? I'm
<BR>&gt; really interested in creating and running large scale quests but
<BR>&gt; I think it would be too hard to do anything big without some
<BR>&gt; help. Thanks in advance...
<BR>
</FONT></td></tr></table></P>
